              <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/28739904/" class="">第154页</a></h3>
          </div>
          <div class="clst">
            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/76940638/" class=" " title="墨似">墨似</a>
                (絆しだな)
              
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="28739904">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">
Fortune is a woman and the prince must know how to conquer the woman, through policies of force, brutality, audacity
The problem of 'dirty hands' if you want to join the political game, you must be prepared to get your hands dirty.
Machiavelli advises the prince always to cultivate the appearance of religion, the prince should appear all mercy, all faith, all honesty, all humanity, and all rel...</span>
                  &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/28739904/">(<span class="">1回应</span>)</a>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2013-09-27 15:04</span>
                  
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="">1人喜欢</span>
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                
Fortune is a woman and the prince must know how to conquer the woman, through policies of force, brutality, audacity<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The problem of 'dirty hands' if you want to join the political game, you must be prepared to get your hands dirty.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Machiavelli advises the prince always to cultivate the appearance of religion, the prince should appear all mercy, all faith, all honesty, all humanity, and all religion. Nothing is more necessary to appear to have this last quality. The appearance of the religion, which means Christianity, is good while the actual is practice of it is harmful.Also in the Republic, when Plato says about justice, his answer to Glaucon, it is important, is it not more important to have the appearance of being just than the reality of it.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>In the Livy strength the difference between two opposed and mutually incompatible moral codes, the Christian and the pagan' If one asks oneself how it come about that people of old in the olden acient world were more fond of liberty than we are today, I think the answer is due to same cause that makes men today less bond than they used to be, and this is due to the difference between our education and that of bygone days. M's emphasis here on moral and religious education is the key difference between the ancient times and his own. Two different ages advanced two very different systems of moral and religious education, one was based on the pagan worldliness and the other based on Christian innocence.The Machiavelli said' our religion has glorified humble and contemplative man rather than the man of action. It assigned as man's highest good humility, abnegation, and contempt for mundane things, whereas the other identified it with maganimity bodily strength, and everything that conduces to make man very bold. The strength of Christian is to suffer rather than do bold thing. By softening the moral, the Christianity has had some deeply perverse effects upon politics, and has made it difficult to develop qualities necessary for the defense of political liberty.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Livy wrote in his book, the man called Numa complited the second founding of Rome. He  dertermined that the Rome, which originally been established through force of arms, should be reestablished though justicem law and religion. The Machiavelli said the religion is not be evaluated by truth content byt for its consequences for society. At the time of founding of the Rome, religion was necessary to temper and control the warlike character of the Romans, but for us today, religion has to serve the opposite purpose , it must instill something of fighting spirit into people who have lost their instinct to resist encroachment on their liberty. The prince should use the religion to encourage his subjects to rely upon their own arms rather than on divine promises.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>If you want Iiberty, you have to konw how not to be good, at least as Christianity has defined goodness, the Christian virtue of humility, turning others cheek, forgiveness of sins, must be rejected, if you want to do good as opposed to just being  good, you have to learn, in other words, how to get your hand dirty.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The true stateman, the prince for Machiavelli must be prepared to mix a love of the common good, a love of his own people, with a streak of cruelty.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>When Crulty is well used, it can be a virtue. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Do not seem to impose your own high-minded innocence, sometimes called justice, for that on the requirements of statecraft, because it will only lead to ruin.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>In the play of Sartre, there is a sentence'Purity is an idea for the yogi or the monk' 'Do you think anyone can govern innocently?' this phrase taken of course from Saint-Just, one of the leaders of the Jacobin Reign of Terror during the French Revolution.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Machiavelli is not actually a Machiavellist, he proceeds to deprecate the virtues of the nobility, the ends of the people is more decent than that of the great, the prince should seek to build his power base on the people rather than on the nobles, because their ambition for power, the nobles will always be threat to the prince and it is an interesting reversal of the Platonic and Aristotelian conception of politics.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Someone have thought Machiavelli's work is really a kind of democrat in disguise and The Prince is intended precisely to alert the prople to the dangers of a usurpatory prince, for example in Spinoza 'Political Treatise, he said Machiavelli is favorable to liberty and the book is kind of a satire on the princely rule. Jean-Jacques Rousseau, from his Social Contract, Machiavelli was an honorable man who being attached to the House of Medici, was forced, during the oppression of his homeland, to disguise his love of freedom. Those two readers took Machiavelli to be an apostle of freedom. Spinoza took his book as a warning to the people about the dangers of princely rule, Rousseau believing that he had deliberately disguised his love of freedom because he had to appeal to the tyrannical nature of the Medici familiy.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The prince must to know how to use the religion but not used by religion, must not  become a dupe of the religious. Politics must become a purely worldly affair, it should not be limited or constrained by any transcendent standards ot moral laws that do not derive from politics itself.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Machiavelli also introduced a new kind of populism. Plato and Aristotle imagined aristocratic republics that would invest in an aristocracy of education and virtue. Machiavelli deliberately seeks to enlist the power of the people against aristocracies of education and virtue. He is a kind of proto-democrat almost who sought to recreate, not through accident and chance, but through planning and design a new kind of republic. The republic that Machiavelli imaged, a new kind of regime, is the one whould be armed and expansive. The republic feeds on conflict, on war and conquest, it is aggressive and imperialistic, which is just the same as the America in the mordern world  
